@node "Disclaimer"

   WorseFormat  is EMAILWARE.  It may be freely distributed as long as no
  more  than  a  nominal  fee is charged to cover time and copying costs.

  All files must remain it their orignal, unmodified forms.

  I  disclaim  any  and all responsibility for any problems that use of
  this program may cause.

  If you use this program often, please send @{"me" link "Author"} an e-mail!

  WorseFormat requires reqtools.library (written by Nico Francois).

@endnode
@node "System Requirements"

  WorseFormat requires the following software...

  - Kickstart V37 (release 2.04) or newer (Kickstart V39 is recommended)

  - ReqTools package V38 or newer (included in the archive)


@endnode

@node "Installation"

  WorseFormat can be installed using the provided Installer script.

  Please note, that this  guide  file  should  be  in  the  same  directory  where
  WorseFormat executable resides.

  The configuration file created by WorseFormat will be saved to that directory as
  well.

@endnode

@node "How to use"

  You can run WorseFormat  both  from  CLI/Shell  and  Workbench.  No  commandline
  parameters or tooltypes are required.

   @{b}Windows:@{ub}
  @{" Main window                  " link MAINWINDOW}
  @{" Device Configuration window  " link CONFIGWINDOW}
  @{" General Configuration window " link MISCWINDOW}
  @{" FileSystem window            " link FSYSWINDOW}
  @{" Bootblock-install window     " link INSTALLWINDOW}

@endnode
@node MAINWINDOW "Main window"

  Main window
  -----------

   @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
  @{" About        " link MainWinAbout}   the upper row of gadgets
  @{" Hide         " link MainWinHide}
  @{" Start!       " link MainWinStart}
  @{" Quit         " link MainWinQuit}

  @{" Drives       " link MainWinDrives}   the big listview
  @{" Refresh      " link MainWinRefresh}

  @{" Driver       " link MainWinDriver}   the Drive Info table
  @{" Unit         " link MainWinUnit}
  @{" Heads        " link MainWinHeads}
  @{" LoCyl        " link MainWinLoCyl}
  @{" HiCyl        " link MainWinHiCyl}
  @{" Blk/Track    " link MainWinBlkTrack}
  @{" Reserved     " link MainWinReserved}

  @{" Quick        " link MainWinQuick}   the checkmark below the Drive Info table

  @{" Format Range " link MainWinFormatRange}
  @{" Verify Range " link MainWinVerifyRange}



   @{b}Menu:@{ub}
  @{FG shine}Project@{FG text}       @{FG shine}Advanced Options@{@FG text}          @{FG shine}Configuration@{@FG text}
  @{" About " link MainWinAbout}      @{" Reset Format Range " link MainWinResetFormatRange}      @{" Edit config           " link MainWinEditConfig}
  @{" Hide  " link MainWinHide}      @{" Reset Verify Range " link MainWinResetVerifyRange}      @{" Edit misc             " link MainWinEditMisc}
  @{" Quit  " link MainWinQuit}      @{" Install bootblock  " link MainWinInstallBootblock}      @{" Load configuration    " link MainWinLoadConfig}
                                          @{" Save as defaults      " link MainWinSaveDefaults}
                                          @{" Save configuration as " link MainWinSaveAs}
@endnode
@node MainWinAbout "About"

  About
  -----

  Pops up a window which displays version information and date of last assemble.

@endnode
@node MainWinHide "Hide"

  Hide
  ----

  Closes the WorseFormat window. Depending on the @{"Hide Method"   link MiscWinHideMethod} setting,
  an icon will be put on your workbench screen ('App Icon'), a sleep window will open
  ('Window')  or  a  new  item  will appear in workbench's tool menu ('App Menu').

@endnode
@node MainWinStart "Start"

  Start!
  ------

  This gadget is the most important one - it starts the formatting routine.
  Before clicking on it, select the device you want to format in the @{"Listview" link MainWinDrives}.
  You should also check the @{"configuration options" link CONFIGWINDOW} for the selected device.

  After clicking on 'Start!', a new window will appear, containing a progress indicator
  and a clock. You may abort the operation by clicking on the window-close gadget.

  WorseFornat will display all bad track numbers in a separate window. However, if the device
  has plenty of errors, the whole operation can be slow down significantly. In such case
  turn this behaviour off - @{"Report bad tracks" link ConfigWinReportBadTracks} option in the @{"Configuration window" link CONFIGWINDOW}.

  When formatting is done, you'll see the @{"File System window" link FSYSWINDOW}.

@endnode
@node MainWinQuit "Quit"

  Quit
  ----

  Will immediately exit the program. Remember to  save  the  configuration  before
  quitting.

@endnode
@node MainWinDrives "Drives"

  Drives
  ------

  This listview shows all DOS devices, that WorseFormat is able to format. Only
  'filesystem' devices with block size equal to 512 bytes appear.
  After selecting one of the entries, WorseFormat will try to obtain some
  information about the device. See @{"Driver" link MainWinDriver}, @{"Unit" link MainWinUnit}, @{"Heads" link MainWinHeads}, @{"LoCyl" link MainWinLoCyl}, @{"HiCyl" link MainWinHiCyl}, @{"Blk/Track" link MainWinBlkTrack}, @{"Reserved" link MainWinReserved}.

  If the displayed information is not accurate or a device is not shown
  on the list, try clicking on @{"Refresh" link MainWinRefresh}.

@endnode
@node MainWinRefresh "Refresh"

  Refresh
  -------

  This gadget refreshes the @{"Drives" link MainWinDrives} listview. Use it
  whenever you mount or dismount a DOS device. You will also need it in case
  of devices which support different disk types (for example, a HD floppy drive,
  which recognizes both DD and HD disks). Just click on this gadget when
  you insert a disk of different type. You may also want to have a look at
  the @{"Inhibit" link ConfigWinInhibitDrive} option in @{"Configuration window" link CONFIGWINDOW}.

@endnode
@node MainWinDriver "Driver"

  Driver
  ------

  This gadget shows the driver of the currently selected DOS device.

@endnode
@node MainWinUnit "Unit"

  Unit
  ----

  This gadget shows unit number of the currently selected DOS device.

@endnode
@node MainWinHeads "Heads"

  Heads
  -----

  This gadget shows amount of heads of the currently selected DOS device.

@endnode
@node MainWinLoCyl "LoCyl"

  LoCyl
  -----

  This gadget shows the number of the first cylinder of the currently selected
  DOS device.

@endnode
@node MainWinHiCyl "HiCyl"

  HiCyl
  -----

  This gadget shows the number of the last cylinder of the currently selected
  DOS device.

@endnode
@node MainWinBlkTrack "Blk/Track"

  Blk/Track
  ---------

  This gadget shows amount of blocks (usually sectors) on every track.

@endnode
@node MainWinReserved "Reserved"

  Reserved
  --------

  This gadget shows amount of blocks (usually sectors) reserved for bootblock.

@endnode
@node MainWinQuick "Quick"

  Quick
  -----

  When this gadget is on, no actual formatting will take place. However, the
  disk will be checked for errors (this will cause all data to be lost, too).

  Turning this option on will shorten the operation. Of course, it's only
  applicable for already formatted disks.

@endnode
@node MainWinFormatRange "Format range"

  Format range
  ------------

  This options is meant for advanced users only. Change these values only
  when you know what you are doing!

  With these two gadgets, you may specify which cylinders should
  be formatted. 'LoCyl' means the first cylinder and 'HiCyl' the last one.

  This option is probably not very useful anyway.

  To return to original values, select @{"Reset format range" link MainWinResetFormatRange} from
  Advanced Options menu.

@endnode
@node MainWinVerifyRange "Verify range"

  Verify range
  ------------

  This option is meant for advanced users only. Change these values only
  when you know what you are doing!

  With these two gadgets, you may specify which cylinders should
  be checked for errors. 'LoCyl' means the first cylinder and 'HiCyl'
  the last one.

  This option is especially useful when you know where the errors are located.

  To return to original values, select @{"Reset verify range" link MainWinResetVerifyRange} from
  Advanced Options menu.

@endnode
@node MainWinResetFormatRange "Reset format range"

  Reset format range
  ------------------

  Select this menu option to restore @{"Format range" link MainWinFormatRange} to original
  values.

@endnode
@node MainWinResetVerifyRange "Reset verify range"

  Reset verify range
  ------------------

  Select this menu option to restore @{"Verify range" link Verify range} to original
  values.

@endnode
@node MainWinInstallBootblock "Install bootblock"

  Install bootblock
  -----------------

  This option is meant for advanced users only.

  With this option, you may change the FileSystemID and Bootblock of the selected
  device. (WorseFormat will recalculate the block checksum)

  The @{"Install window" link INSTALLWINDOW} will open after clicking here.

@endnode
@node MainWinEditConfig "Edit config"

  Edit config
  -----------

  The @{"configuration window" link CONFIGWINDOW} will open after selecting this option.

@endnode
@node MainWinEditMisc "Edit misc"

  Edit misc
  ---------

  The @{"general configuration window" link MISCWINDOW} will open after selecting
  this option.

@endnode
@node MainWinLoadConfig "Load configuration"

  Load configuration
  ------------------

  A file-requester will pop up, allowing you to select a configuration file
  to load.

@endnode
@node MainWinSaveDefaults "Save defaults"

  Save defaults
  -------------

  The current configuration will be saved to PROGDIR:WorseFormat.prefs.
  This file is loaded by WorseFormat at startup.

@endnode
@node MainWinSaveAs "Save configuration as"

  Save configuration as
  ---------------------

  A file-requester will pop up, allowing you to choose where current
  configuration should be saved. Default configuration file is
  PROGDIR:WorseFormat.prefs.

@endnode
@node CONFIGWINDOW "Device Configuration window"

  Device Configuration window
  ---------------------------

  In this window you can set additional device-specific options.

    @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
   @{" Listview            " link ConfigWinList}
   @{" Add                 " link ConfigWinAdd}
   @{" Remove              " link ConfigWinRemove}

   @{" Device              " link ConfigWinDevice}
   @{" Name                " link ConfigWinName}
   @{" Unit                " link ConfigWinUnit}

   @{" Report bad tracks   " link ConfigWinReportBadTracks}
   @{" Create BadBlockFile " link ConfigWinCreateBadBlockFile}
   @{" Inhibit drive       " link ConfigWinInhibitDrive}
   @{" Motor control       " link ConfigWinMotorControl}
   @{" Read drive geometry " link ConfigWinReadDriveGeometry}

   @{" Verify mode         " link ConfigWinVerifyMode}
   @{" Verify level        " link ConfigWinVerifyLevel}

   @{" Save                " link ConfigWinSave}
   @{" Use                 " link ConfigWinUse}
   @{" Cancel              " link ConfigWinCancel}

@endnode
@node ConfigWinList "Device list"

  Device list
  -----------

  All configured devices are listed here. When you select an entry,
  all related configuration info will appear in the right part of
  the window.

  Click on @{"Add" link ConfigWinAdd}/@{"Remove" link ConfigWinRemove} to add/remove an entry.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinAdd "Add config entry"

  Add config entry
  ----------------

  A @{"requester" link ADDWINDOW} will pop up after clicking on this gadget. Select device
  to add by double-clicking on an entry or by clicking on 'OK'.

  If the device you want to add is not shown on the list, select
  'new device'. You'll have to specify @{"DOS name" link ConfigWinName}, @{"device" link ConfigWinDevice}
  and @{"unit" link ConfigWinUnit} yourself in this case.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinRemove "Remove config entry"

  Remove config entry
  -------------------

  Use this option to remove the selected configuration entry.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinDevice "Device driver"

  Device
  ------

  This gadget shows name of the driver of the currently selected device.

  Usually, you won't need to change this string. The most casual situation
  when you must edit it is when you @{"add" link ConfigWinAdd} a '(new device)'.

  Device name, @{"DOS name" link ConfigWinName} and @{"unit number" link ConfigWinUnit} are used by WorseFormat to identify
  dos devices. The configuration entry will be used by @{"Start!" link MainWinStart} and @{"Install bootblock" link MainWinInstallBootblock}
  only when these three values match the device selected in @{"Drives list" link MainWinDrives}.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinName "DOS name"

  DOS Name
  --------

  This gadget shows the DOS name of the currently selected device.

  Usually, you won't need to change this string. The most casual situation
  when you must edit it is when you @{"add" link ConfigWinAdd} a '(new device)'.

  @{"Device name" link ConfigWinDevice}, DOS name and @{"unit number" link ConfigWinUnit} are used by WorseFormat to identify
  dos devices. The configuration entry will be used by @{"Start!" link MainWinStart} and @{"Install bootblock" link MainWinInstallBootblock}
  only when these three values match the device selected in @{"Drive list" link MainWinDrives}.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinUnit "Unit number"

  Unit number
  -----------

  This gadget shows the unit number of the currently selected device.

  Usually, you won't need to change this value. The most casual situation
  when you must edit it is when you @{"add" link ConfigWinAdd} a '(new device)'.

  @{"Device name" link ConfigWinDevice}, @{"DOS name" link ConfigWinName} and unit number are used by WorseFormat to identify
  dos devices. The configuration entry will be used by @{"Start!" link MainWinStart} and @{"Install bootblock" link MainWinInstallBootblock}
  only when these three values match the device selected in @{"Drive list" link MainWinDrives}.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinReportBadTracks "Report bad tracks"

  Report bad tracks
  -----------------

  When this option is on, WorseFormat will open a special window during
  formatting, in which numbers of damaged tracks will be displayed.

  However, if the disk has a lot erros, this can significantly slow down
  the operation. You should turn this option off in such case.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinCreateBadBlockFile "Create BadBlockFile"

  Create BadBlockFile
  -------------------

  When this option is turned off, no BadBlockFile will be created. This can
  save some disk space (typically 0.5-5KB, depending on disk size and amount
  of errors), but bad blocks won't be fully protected. This means, you'll
  be able to write to this disk as long as the Disk-Validator doesn't
  recalculate DiskBitMap.

  This option should generally be left on. Only in cases where amount of
  free disk space is critical, think about turning it off.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinInhibitDrive "Inhibit drive"

  Inhibit drive
  -------------

  When this option is on, then WorseFormat will block any activity
  of the disk handler (i.e. filesystem). It's usually useful to have
  this option turned on, because it prevents the bad disk from being
  validated/read by the filesystem immediately after inserting it
  into the drive.

  WorseFormat gets all information about the disk layout from the
  DOS database - it doesn't fully use the low-level disk geometry data
  (even when @{"Read drive geometry" link ConfigWinReadDriveGeometry} is on).
  In case of some drives supporting different disk types (like a floppy
  HD station, which supports both DD and HD disks) this database won't
  be correctly updated when Inhibit is on. For example, let's say
  there's a DD disk in a HD drive. Now, when you press on @{"Start!" link MainWinStart} (with
  Inhibit option turned on) filesystem will be inhibited. If you remove
  the DD disk and insert a HD one now, the filesystem won't know about it.
  That means, WorseFormat will also think, that there's still a DD disk inside.
  To prevent such problems, always leave this option OFF for drives
  which support different disk types.

  It's usually OK to turn this option on for hard drives.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinMotorControl "Motor control"

  Motor control
  -------------

  When this option is on, WorseFormat will control the disk drive with
  the TD_MOTOR command. However, there are some old device drivers
  (mainly A500 old hard disk controllers), which doesn't support this
  command correctly or handle it improperly, causing Enforcer hits
  (i.e. el500hd.device).

  This option should generally be turned on. Turn it off only
  for old A500 hard disk drivers (i.e. those designed for
  Kickstart 1.2).

@endnode
@node ConfigWinReadDriveGeometry "Read drive geometry"

  Read drive geometry
  -------------------

  When this option is on, WorseFormat will read the drive geometry
  with the TD_GETGEOMETRY command in order to calculate disk layout more
  accurately. However, TD_GETGEOMETRY has been introduced in Kickstart 2.0,
  and all pre-2.0 disk drivers don't support it.

  IT'S VERY DANGEROUS TO TURN THIS OPTION ON FOR OLD DRIVERS. You may
  cause the whole hard disk (not only the selected partition) to be
  formatted this way (especially the RDB area is in danger).

  You may safely turn this option on for trackdisk.device. For all other
  drivers (INCLUDING scsi.device) it's better to leave it off.

  Please note: turning this option on for drives that support multiple
  disk types is not enough. Have a look @{"here" link ConfigWinInhibitDrive}.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinVerifyMode "Verify mode"

  Verify mode
  -----------

  Two modes are available: 'read' and 'read/write'. The latter is much
  more accurate, but it is slower.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinVerifyLevel "Verify level"

  Verify level
  ------------

  Select a number from range 1-99. The higher the number, the more
  accurate the verification routine will be. Of course, higher
  verification levels also take more time.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinSave "Save configuration"

  Save
  ----

  Click here to save current configuration to PROGDIR:WorseFormat.prefs.
  This file will be loaded by WorseFormat at startup time.
  The Configuration window will be closed after using
  this gadget.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinUse "Use configuration"

  Use
  ---

  Click here to accept changes, without saving the configuration file.
  Current configuration will be lost after quitting WorseFormat.
  The Configuration window will be closed after using
  this gadget.

@endnode
@node ConfigWinCancel "Cancel configuration"

  Cancel
  ------

  Click here to cancel all changes and close the Configuration window.

@endnode
@node "Introduction"

  WorseFormat is able to format partially damaged disks by creating a special 'bad
  block file', which contains all damaged sectors.

  This way the formatted disks are usable again, but of course their  capacity  is
  smaller.

  However, there is a restriction: the first track and the track in the middle  of
  the disk mustn't contain errors.

  Features of WorseFormat include:

  - full intuition.library-based Graphical User Interface
  - four filesystems supported: OFS, FFS, International OFS and International FFS
  - advanced verification routine
  - supports almost all standard DOS drives
  - quick-format mode supported
  - formats undamaged disks for any filesystem (the FileSystem format option)
  - you can specify track ranges for Format and Verify stages
  - a simple bootblock installer implemented
  - configuration file

@endnode
@node MISCWINDOW "General configuration window"

  General configuration window
  ----------------------------

  You can invoke this window by selecting @{"Edit misc" link MainWinEditMisc} from the Configuration menu.

   @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
  @{" Beep when an error occurs    " link MiscWinBeepErrors}
  @{" Beep when formatting is done " link MiscWinBeepDone}

  @{" Hide method                  " link MiscWinHideMethod}
  @{" Hide icon                    " link MiscWinHideIcon}

  @{" Create icons                 " link MiscWinCreateIcons}
  @{" Trashcan icon                " link MiscWinTrashcanIcon}

  @{" Default disk label           " link MiscWinDefaultDiskLabel}
  @{" Default BadBlockFile         " link MiscWinDefaultBBF}
  @{" Default filesystem           " link MiscWinDefaultFSys}
  @{" Default bootblock            " link MiscWinDefaultBB}

  @{" Save                         " link ConfigWinSave}
  @{" Use                          " link ConfigWinUse}
  @{" Cancel                       " link ConfigWinCancel}

@endnode
@node MiscWinBeepErrors "Beep when an error occurs"

  Beep when an error occurs
  -------------------------

  WorseFormat will beep when an error is detected.

  Useful when formatting large hard disks.

@endnode
@node MiscWinBeepDone "Beep when formatting is done"

  Beep when formatting is done
  ----------------------------

  WorseFormat will beep when formatting is completed.

  Useful when formatting large hard disks.

@endnode
@node MiscWinHideMethod "Hide method"

  Hide method
  -----------

  Three modes are implemented:

  - Window - a little window will open after using the command 'Hide'. Close it to quit
   WorseFormat, press right mouse button to get back to the program.

  - App Menu - a new item will be added to the workbench Tools menu.

  - App Icon - an appicon will appear on your workbench screen. You may specify an icon
   in the @{"Hide icon" link MiscWinHideIcon} gadget.

@endnode
@node MiscWinHideIcon "Hide icon"

  Hide icon
  ---------

  You can specify filename of the icon to use during 'Hide'

@endnode
@node MiscWinCreateIcons "Create icons"

  Create icons
  ------------

  Turn this option on if you want Trashcans to be created.
  You'll have to specify an icon for the Trashcan as well - see @{"Trashcan icon" link MiscWinTrashcanIcon}.

@endnode
@node MiscWinTrashcanIcon "Trashcan icon"

  Trashcan icon
  -------------

  Set an icon for Trashcan here.

@endnode
@node MiscWinDefaultDiskLabel "Default disk label"

  Default disk label
  ------------------

  You can specify the default disk name here. See @{"Disk label" link FSysDiskLabel}.

@endnode
@node MiscWinDefaultBBF "Default BadBlockFile"

  Default BadBlockFile
  --------------------

  You can specify the default filename here. See @{"BadBlockFile" link FSysBadBlockFile}.

@endnode
@node MiscWinDefaultFSys "Default filesystem"

  Default filesystem
  ------------------

  Youo can set the default filesystem here. See @{"Filesystem" link FSysFileSystem}.

@endnode
@node MiscWinDefaultBB "Defaultl bootblock"

  Default bootblock
  -----------------

  You can set the defaultl bootblock here. See @{"Bootblock" link FSysInstall}.

@endnode
@node FSYSWINDOW "FileSystem window"

  FileSystem window
  -----------------

  This window appears when formatting is completed.

   @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
 @{" Bad blocks         " link FSysBadBlocks}
 @{" Disk label         " link FSysDiskLabel}
 @{" BadBlockFile       " link FSysBadBlockFile}
 @{" File system        " link FSysFileSystem}
 @{" Install            " link FSysInstall}
 @{" File system format " link FSysFileSystemFormat}

 @{" OK                 " link FSysOK}
 @{" Cancel             " link FSysCancel}
@endnode
@node FSysBadBlocks "Bad blocks"

  Bad blocks
  ----------

  This gadget shows the amount of detected bad blocks.

@endnode
@node FSysDiskLabel "Disk label"

  Disk label
  ----------

  You can enter name for the formatted disk here.

@endnode
@node FSysBadBlockFile "Bad block filename"

  BadBlockFile
  ------------

  You can specify name for the BadBlock file here. '.bad' is default.

@endnode
@node FSysFileSystem "File system"

  File system
  -----------

  You can select a filesystem for the disk here. Currently, only four
  are supported:
  - Old File System (OFS)
  - Fast File System (FFS)
  - Old File System International (OFS-Int)
  - Fast File System International (FFS-Int)

  Filesystems with directory cache aren't supported yet.

@endnode
@node FSysInstall "Install"

  Install
  -------

  You can select a bootblock for the disk. The choices are:
  - Standard Boot - as in DOS V1.2/1.3
  - No Boot - the disk won't be bootable
  - Silent Start - the standard boot code for DOS V2.0-3.1
  - VirusCheck - a simple virus-killer
  - VirusCheck SS - a simple virus-killer with Silent Start feature

  Bootblocks are not important for hard disks.

@endnode
@node FSysFileSystemFormat "File system format"

  FileSystem format
  -----------------

  This mode is available only for undamaged disks (i.e. BadBlocks must
  be zero).

  When it's on, WorseFormat will not use its internal disk-initializing
  routines. Instead, it will ask the filesystem of this device to initialize
  the disk. This way you can format AFS, PFS or PC-DOS disks.

@endnode
@node FSysOK "OK"

  OK
  --

  Click here to init the disk.

@endnode
@node FSysCancel "Cancel"

  Cancel
  ------

  Click here to abort the operation.

@endnode
@node INSTALLWINDOW "Bootblock-install window"

 Bootblock-install window
 ------------------------

 This window appears after selecting @{"Install bootblock" link MainWinInstallBootblock} from the Advanced Options
 menu.

  @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
 @{" Dos type    " link iDosType}
 @{" File system " link iFileSystem}
 @{" Bootblock   " link iBootBlock}

 @{" Install     " link iOK}
 @{" Cancel      " link iCancel}

@endnode
@node iDosType "Dos type"

  Dos type
  --------

  Current DosType will be displayed in the right gadget.
  WorseFormat will try to identify it - see the left gadget.

@endnode
@node iFileSystem "File system"

  File system
  -----------

  You can change the DosType of the disk here.

  Handle with care!

@endnode
@node iBootBlock "Bootblock"

  Bootblock
  ---------

  You can change the Bootblock of the disk here.

  Handle with care!

@endnode
@node iOK "Install"

  Install
  -------

  Accept changes and save them to disk.

@endnode
@node iCancel "Cancel"

  Cancel
  ------

  Cancel changes. Nothing will be written to disk.

@endnode
@node ADDWINDOW "Add config entry"

 Add config entry - requester
 ----------------------------

   @{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
  @{" Listview " link addList}
  @{" Add      " link addOK}
  @{" Cancel   " link addCancel}

@endnode
@node addList "The listview"

  The listview
  ------------

  Select a device to add. Double-click on an entry to accept it.

@endnode
@node addOK "Add"

  Add
  ---

  Accept and add currenty selected entry.

@endnode
@node addCancel "Cancel"

  Cancel
  ------

  Cancel the requester. No entries will be added.

@endnode

